{{orphan|date=June 2010}}
'''Gin'nnah Muhammad''' (pronounced /jenna)  (born in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]],  July, 1963), is a [[Muslim]] [[African American]] woman who was dismissed from a [[Michigan]] small claims court in 2006 by a judge because she was wearing a veil (as required under [[Islam]]). The judge claimed he needed to see her face to assess her truthfulness.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=950CEFD7153BF93BA25755C0A96F9C8B63| work=[[The New York Times]]| agency=[[Associated Press]]| date=June 18, 2009| title=Michigan Judges Can Regulate Dress in Court| accessdate=2015-10-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Mich.: Witnesses May Have To Remove Veil| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/06/17/national/main5093829.shtml| work=[[CBS News]]| date=June 17, 2009| accessdate=2015-10-22}}</ref>

In 2009 Gin'nnah Muhammad went on to the [[Michigan Supreme Court]] and spoke to the panel of judges wearing her veil. The result was that the court ruled that judges could regulate the clothing of witnesses.

